Optical discs are a type of storage media that use laser technology to store and access digital data. They are commonly used in the form of a compact disc (CD), digital versatile disc (DVD), and Blu-ray disc (BD).The earliest optical disc was invented in 1958 by James T. Russell, a businessman and inventor who developed the first commercial optical digital storage medium. The storage medium used a thin coating of crystalline material that could be read and written to using a laser. Russells invention was called the LaserDisc.The first commercially available optical disc was